WEBVTT

00:00.913 --> 00:03.177
in Maine
from my cousin Stephen.

00:03.307 --> 00:05.657
Even has a name:
Chapelwaite.

00:05.788 --> 00:07.572
You must be Charles Boone,
the sea captain?

00:07.703 --> 00:09.183
These are my children.

00:09.313 --> 00:10.401
Is there a Mrs. Boone coming?

00:10.532 --> 00:12.316
My wife passed.

00:12.447 --> 00:14.405
[Ann Morgan] Rebecca Morgan,
you're a writer.

00:14.536 --> 00:16.494
[Rebecca] There's only one
good story in town, Mother.

00:16.625 --> 00:19.454
Good day. I hear
you're looking for a governess.

00:19.584 --> 00:22.283
- Who's the little girl?
- Must be Marcella.

00:22.413 --> 00:25.373
Stephen's daughter.
She passed away.

00:25.503 --> 00:27.549
How come you never talk
about your father?

00:27.679 --> 00:30.639
He was a peculiar man.

00:30.769 --> 00:32.684
- [cries out]
- [Charles gasps]

00:32.815 --> 00:35.513
I'm afraid we have rats.

00:35.644 --> 00:37.341
They're being clever now.

00:37.472 --> 00:39.256
Your family has a reputation,
Mr. Boone.

00:39.387 --> 00:41.432
Stephen was a part of that.

00:41.563 --> 00:43.217
- I would sell the mill and go.
- Well, I have other plans.

00:43.347 --> 00:44.392
Your father--

00:44.522 --> 00:45.567
Father was
Phillip Boone's lawyer

00:45.697 --> 00:47.482
and he lived in fear of the man,
I am aware.

00:47.612 --> 00:49.527
We prayed we'd seen
the last Boone.

00:49.658 --> 00:51.486
And why is that?

00:51.616 --> 00:53.749
Some blame Chapelwaite
for the illness in town.

00:53.879 --> 00:54.793
What about you, Edward?

00:54.924 --> 00:57.318
Your little Susan's sick.

00:57.448 --> 00:59.407
Let's send
these new Boones packing.

00:59.537 --> 01:00.669
Burn it then.

01:00.799 --> 01:02.453
- Who goes there?
- [horse neighs]

01:04.325 --> 01:06.414
[gurgling]

01:08.633 --> 01:11.941
There's something
that you hide from us.

01:12.072 --> 01:13.508
- [glass shatters]
- [Charles' father] It's coming.

01:13.638 --> 01:14.683
The worm.

01:14.813 --> 01:16.293
It scares me.

01:17.686 --> 01:21.124
[whip-poor-wills singing]

01:31.526 --> 01:34.268
[wind blowing]

01:34.398 --> 01:35.704
[woman screaming]

01:39.534 --> 01:41.318
- [screaming in pain]
- You're doing very well.

01:41.449 --> 01:42.798
You're doing very well.

01:42.928 --> 01:43.668
- No!
- Breathe, breathe.

01:43.799 --> 01:45.279
Get it out!

01:45.409 --> 01:46.628
Your baby's breached, Faith.

01:46.758 --> 01:49.761
We don't have much time.
You need to push now!

01:49.892 --> 01:51.285
- [crying and grunting]
- Come on. That's it. That's it.

01:51.415 --> 01:53.548
Breathe!
Well done, one more.

01:53.678 --> 01:54.636
The baby's coming!

01:54.766 --> 01:56.812
Gentle pushes now.
Gentle.

01:56.942 --> 01:58.422
- Little pushes.
- [moaning]

01:58.553 --> 02:00.511
Push! Push!

02:00.642 --> 02:01.686
[crying, moaning in pain]

02:01.817 --> 02:04.559
[baby crying at odd pitch]

02:07.823 --> 02:10.521
- Hello.
- [odd crying continues]

02:14.482 --> 02:16.788
- God help us.
- [distracted] What?

02:16.919 --> 02:19.139
I want to see my baby.

02:20.792 --> 02:23.621
- Please. Let me see her.
- Him.

02:23.752 --> 02:26.276
- It's a boy.
- A boy.

02:32.543 --> 02:34.328
No.

02:34.458 --> 02:37.157
[crying continues]

02:39.507 --> 02:41.378
No!

04:15.603 --> 04:19.868
[birds and insects chirping]

04:34.012 --> 04:41.324
♪♪♪

05:10.875 --> 05:12.921
Good morning, Miss Morgan.

05:14.879 --> 05:16.533
Mr. Boone.
You were out early.

05:16.664 --> 05:17.621
I was.

05:19.667 --> 05:21.973
I'm taking Loa to town.

05:22.104 --> 05:24.411
We'll meet you
and the other two at school.

05:26.108 --> 05:28.719
What have you found?

05:28.850 --> 05:31.069
I was admiring your books

05:31.200 --> 05:33.898
and I--I came across
these old letters

05:34.029 --> 05:35.813
between my father
and the Boones.

05:35.944 --> 05:37.946
He was their attorney.

05:38.076 --> 05:39.817
Some bear
my father's signature.

05:39.948 --> 05:41.950
You knew he worked
for my uncle and cousin?

05:42.080 --> 05:43.995
I did.

05:44.126 --> 05:46.346
I'm sorry.
I should've mentioned that.

05:49.871 --> 05:53.570
And what was his opinion
of them?

05:53.701 --> 05:56.965
My father was intimidated
by Phillip.

05:57.095 --> 05:59.750
Hmm. I see.

05:59.881 --> 06:03.972
Well, if the letters have
any meaning to you, keep them.

06:04.102 --> 06:05.930
They don't.

06:06.061 --> 06:09.586
My father left
for New York when I was 15

06:09.717 --> 06:10.979
to grow his law practice.

06:11.109 --> 06:13.329
We haven't heard from him since.

06:13.460 --> 06:15.592
Apparently,
he started a second family

06:15.723 --> 06:17.507
and abandoned them as well.

06:22.730 --> 06:23.774
They're yours
if you want them.

06:25.602 --> 06:26.647
Loa?

06:45.622 --> 06:47.668
[sheep bleating]

06:52.368 --> 06:54.414
Daniel.
Daniel.

06:56.807 --> 06:59.593
- Mornin', Rose.
- Mornin'.

06:59.723 --> 07:00.811
Have you seen Edward?

07:00.942 --> 07:03.118
Not since yesterday
at the tavern.

07:03.248 --> 07:05.816
Susan saw him leave
last night with the wagon.

07:05.947 --> 07:08.732
Did he say where he was going?

07:08.863 --> 07:10.560
He didn't say, Rose.

07:12.040 --> 07:13.737
He never came home.

07:17.088 --> 07:20.744
Well, we're on our way
to the mill.

07:20.875 --> 07:22.790
If he's there,
I'll send him home.

07:24.748 --> 07:25.923
Thank you, Daniel.

07:33.888 --> 07:36.760
What'd that damn fool
get himself into, huh?

07:49.294 --> 07:50.948
It's okay.
You can trust me.

07:58.216 --> 08:00.828
How old was your daughter
when she contracted the disease?

08:00.958 --> 08:03.091
She was three.

08:03.221 --> 08:06.877
Our ship's purser
took a bribe,

08:07.008 --> 08:09.097
sent us off with casks
of spoiled beef.

08:09.227 --> 08:11.491
The food wasn't fit for hogs.

08:15.103 --> 08:18.106
No one knows the exact cause
of rickets, Mr. Boone.

08:18.236 --> 08:20.195
Her leg is stronger
than it looks.

08:20.325 --> 08:22.980
I'm going to prescribe
a vitamin rub and elixir.

08:24.895 --> 08:26.723
We've seen doctors
in every port

08:26.854 --> 08:29.030
from here to the Crozets.

08:29.160 --> 08:32.337
They all prescribe some
variation of the same thing.

08:32.468 --> 08:33.991
I was hoping...

08:36.385 --> 08:38.213
We're open to anything new.

08:38.343 --> 08:40.694
I'm afraid I don't have
anything like that.

08:48.005 --> 08:49.093
[horse neighs]

08:56.057 --> 08:56.927
[boy]
You don't belong here.

09:05.283 --> 09:07.068
Good luck today.

09:07.198 --> 09:08.809
I want to go home.

09:08.939 --> 09:10.811
We are home.

09:14.075 --> 09:15.685
Go on.

09:30.047 --> 09:32.180
There you go.
Okay?

09:34.399 --> 09:36.227
Good morning, Headmaster Fish.

09:36.358 --> 09:38.229
Are you sure about this,
Miss Morgan?

09:38.360 --> 09:40.101
It is a public school.

09:40.231 --> 09:41.711
No birth certificates,
I presume?

09:41.842 --> 09:43.017
No.

09:43.147 --> 09:44.888
Any particular nation
or tribe?

09:45.019 --> 09:47.325
- We were born on ship.
- The Narwhal.

09:47.456 --> 09:49.327
Have you been vaccinated
for smallpox?

09:49.458 --> 09:51.895
- Yes.
- Proof of residency?

09:52.026 --> 09:53.593
Really, Henry?

09:56.030 --> 09:57.858
Children, heed your teachers
and monitors.

10:01.905 --> 10:02.863
Look after each other.

10:02.993 --> 10:04.865
The first day is
always the worst.

10:04.995 --> 10:06.083
Come on.

10:19.880 --> 10:26.887
♪♪♪

10:34.372 --> 10:38.072
We lost the twins
two years ago in July.

10:38.202 --> 10:40.030
- To the illness?
- Yes.

10:40.161 --> 10:42.032
I'm sorry.

10:42.163 --> 10:43.643
Thank you.

10:46.297 --> 10:49.083
The photo was my wife's idea.

10:50.258 --> 10:52.260
A grim reminder.

10:52.390 --> 10:54.262
As if one could ever forget.

10:58.048 --> 11:00.181
The little girl behind them...

11:00.311 --> 11:02.139
- is that Marcella Boone?
- It is.

11:02.270 --> 11:05.099
They were playmates.

11:05.229 --> 11:08.015
Well, Minister,
I have a favor to ask.

11:10.060 --> 11:11.801
I'd like to address
your congregation.

11:11.932 --> 11:13.281
Uh-huh.

11:13.411 --> 11:15.239
This will be a--
a business proposal

11:15.370 --> 11:17.328
for myself and the town.

11:17.459 --> 11:19.461
Uh, I need 10 minutes
of their time.

11:19.591 --> 11:21.332
Well, I can't just
hand you the pulpit.

11:21.463 --> 11:25.510
I know my flock;
they'll crucify us both.

11:25.641 --> 11:31.168
But if you were
to come by an informal event,

11:31.299 --> 11:35.956
like today's social,
I could give you the floor.

11:36.086 --> 11:38.001
- Today?
- Four o'clock.

11:38.132 --> 11:39.002
Would you be ready?

11:40.264 --> 11:41.265
I will be.

11:43.528 --> 11:45.705
Thank you.
Thank you, sir.

11:50.492 --> 11:54.104
Minister, your twins.

11:56.498 --> 12:00.154
Do you believe my family
was responsible in any way

12:00.284 --> 12:02.199
for the illness
that befell yours?

12:03.984 --> 12:05.246
I do not.

12:10.164 --> 12:11.731
Good day.

12:15.169 --> 12:18.041
[crows caw]

12:26.833 --> 12:31.359
[horse snorts
and neighs nervously]

12:31.489 --> 12:33.230
What is it?

12:33.361 --> 12:35.102
Hey, boy, what is it?

12:42.370 --> 12:44.111
May I help you?

12:44.241 --> 12:45.852
[horse whinnies loudly]

12:48.332 --> 12:52.206
[horse snorts]

13:09.397 --> 13:11.268
The worm is calling.

13:12.574 --> 13:18.232
[whip-poor-wills chirp]

13:18.362 --> 13:22.149
Unorganized territory,
Minnesota territory,

13:22.279 --> 13:25.282
California, Mexican Cession,

13:25.413 --> 13:27.415
Oregon territory.

13:27.545 --> 13:29.591
- Very good, Emory.
- Thank you.

13:29.721 --> 13:31.201
Now...

13:34.074 --> 13:35.205
Loa Boone.

13:37.164 --> 13:40.036
Will you please show us

13:40.167 --> 13:43.431
where the
Kingdom of Hawaii is?

14:15.289 --> 14:16.159
[clears throat]

14:23.601 --> 14:24.385
- [foot makes contact]
- [gasps]

14:24.515 --> 14:26.126
- Loa!
- [laughs]

14:26.256 --> 14:27.562
- You tripped her!
- Tane!

14:27.692 --> 14:29.303
Tane! Tane!
Marcus!

14:29.433 --> 14:30.652
That is enough!

14:30.782 --> 14:32.306
Enough.

14:32.436 --> 14:33.960
No!

14:35.657 --> 14:37.398
Emory!
You sit down!

14:39.313 --> 14:41.010
Back to your seat!

14:41.141 --> 14:42.055
Tane!
To your seat!

14:42.185 --> 14:44.144
Marcus, now!

14:44.274 --> 14:46.886
[screams]

14:51.281 --> 14:53.066
I hate it here.

14:53.196 --> 14:55.242
I won't stay.

14:55.372 --> 14:57.070
You can't leave.

14:57.200 --> 14:58.898
Where would you go?

15:04.294 --> 15:06.644
Loa?

15:06.775 --> 15:09.430
Sorry about what happened
at school.

15:15.566 --> 15:18.047
Are you all right?

15:18.178 --> 15:19.701
[sighs]

15:19.831 --> 15:21.964
I'll speak to
your teacher tomorrow.

15:24.271 --> 15:26.099
Was there any
good part of your day?

15:27.535 --> 15:29.363
Either of you?

15:30.320 --> 15:33.236
All right, we'll go over
your homework after supper.

15:40.287 --> 15:42.550
They say the baby is
grotesque.

15:42.680 --> 15:45.118
It has no eyes.

15:46.510 --> 15:48.686
Be better
it had been stillborn.

15:48.817 --> 15:51.472
A woman who had buried
two of her own

15:51.602 --> 15:53.300
might have more sympathy.

15:53.430 --> 15:55.128
I have sympathy
for the child,

15:55.258 --> 15:58.000
not the mother.

15:58.131 --> 16:01.351
Lord only knows what she's done
to deserve such a burden.

16:03.788 --> 16:07.749
People think it's an omen.

16:07.879 --> 16:09.577
It's not.

16:09.707 --> 16:12.406
Where did she come from?
Why won't she say?

16:12.536 --> 16:15.626
Her constant distress is an act.

16:15.757 --> 16:18.281
Clearly she's not so timid
in the sheets.

16:18.412 --> 16:20.066
You sound just like
your father, Alice.

16:22.329 --> 16:24.113
Faith Pringle is a whore.

16:26.550 --> 16:28.813
And whoever...

16:28.944 --> 16:30.554
[lowers her voice]
whoever the father is

16:30.685 --> 16:33.166
of that bastard child
is a coward.

16:34.428 --> 16:37.561
[indistinct chatter]

16:44.438 --> 16:45.656
Everybody.

16:45.787 --> 16:47.876
Your attention, please.

16:48.007 --> 16:51.619
Thank you for all this delicious
food and for sharing.

16:51.749 --> 16:53.708
It's such a wonderful way
to remind us

16:53.838 --> 16:55.797
how blessed we all are.

16:55.927 --> 16:59.714
I have a few announcements
to make, but first,

16:59.844 --> 17:03.674
we have a guest who would like
to say a few words.

17:03.805 --> 17:06.286
Mr. Boone?
Please.

17:06.416 --> 17:09.419
- Don't let him.
- [disgruntled chatter]

17:09.550 --> 17:11.639
- Is he mad?
- Please! Please.

17:11.769 --> 17:12.640
Please give our guest

17:12.770 --> 17:15.425
the respect of your attention.

17:20.256 --> 17:21.518
Thank you.

17:23.477 --> 17:24.521
Thank you, Minister Burroughs.
[clears throat]

17:24.652 --> 17:26.654
And thank you all

17:26.784 --> 17:28.612
for giving me
a moment of your time.

17:28.743 --> 17:31.224
My name is Charles Boone.

17:31.354 --> 17:33.574
I came to Maine with a vision.

17:33.704 --> 17:37.404
I intend to expand production
at the Boone sawmill

17:37.534 --> 17:39.797
and to use its lumber

17:39.928 --> 17:42.931
to build ships
along the Androscoggin.

17:43.062 --> 17:46.326
Within two years, this yard
will produce cargo ships

17:46.456 --> 17:48.589
with a steel hull,

17:48.719 --> 17:50.808
powered by both sail and steam,

17:50.939 --> 17:53.376
faster than any clipper at sea.

17:53.507 --> 17:55.683
Now, what this means
for Preacher's Corners,

17:55.813 --> 17:57.380
and for all of you...

17:59.556 --> 18:00.731
is prosperity.

18:00.862 --> 18:03.517
He'll transport
our wealth to his.

18:03.647 --> 18:05.214
- [crowd murmuring]
- That is not true, sir.

18:08.609 --> 18:09.914
[man]
Let him speak, Samuel.

18:10.045 --> 18:13.396
I understand there
is a lingering animosity

18:13.527 --> 18:14.615
towards my family.

18:17.487 --> 18:19.620
I can't take responsibility
for their misdeeds,

18:19.750 --> 18:21.970
but I--I can give you my word

18:22.101 --> 18:25.278
that no further wrongs will
come from me or my children.

18:25.408 --> 18:26.496
[man]
What about the illness?

18:26.627 --> 18:28.194
What new diseases
do these Boones carry?

18:28.324 --> 18:29.673
None, Madame.

18:29.804 --> 18:31.675
- But we need work!
- And I need men.

18:31.806 --> 18:35.331
Please,
don't let old prejudice

18:35.462 --> 18:36.724
impede our shared progress.

18:36.854 --> 18:38.726
I mean to build ships.

18:38.856 --> 18:42.556
I'll pay 50 men top wage
to start this venture with me.

18:42.686 --> 18:45.515
I'll be taking names,
tomorrow noon,

18:45.646 --> 18:48.301
outside the tavern.

18:48.431 --> 18:50.651
[crowd whispering indistinctly]

18:50.781 --> 18:53.306
Good day. Thank you.

18:53.436 --> 18:54.437
Thank you.

19:09.365 --> 19:10.671
[knocks]

19:15.763 --> 19:17.504
Minister Burroughs.

19:17.634 --> 19:19.462
What brings you out so late?

19:19.593 --> 19:21.334
Oh, I was told that
Faith Pringle had her child.

19:21.464 --> 19:23.249
She did.

19:23.379 --> 19:24.641
Is it true?

19:24.772 --> 19:26.469
It is.

19:29.646 --> 19:31.344
[baby rasps softly]

19:33.824 --> 19:36.305
- [knocking]
- Faith.

19:37.828 --> 19:39.569
It's Mr. Burroughs.

19:42.485 --> 19:43.486
Come in.

20:01.591 --> 20:03.419
Hey.

20:03.550 --> 20:06.683
- [shushing]
- [cries]

20:06.814 --> 20:10.296
- [sobs]
- Hey, hey, hey.

20:16.998 --> 20:19.348
I want to see our child.

20:27.530 --> 20:29.402
[raspy breathing]

20:29.532 --> 20:31.665
It's because of me.

20:31.795 --> 20:35.495
God punished me for the things
I did before we met.

20:35.625 --> 20:37.497
Not my God.

20:39.934 --> 20:41.544
[baby fusses]

20:41.675 --> 20:43.024
Easy, child.

20:43.154 --> 20:45.461
Easy, easy.

20:45.592 --> 20:47.376
There are other gods, Martin.

20:48.812 --> 20:50.814
It scares me

20:50.945 --> 20:52.903
that something so wicked
could grow inside me.

20:53.034 --> 20:55.863
Oh, never say that.

20:55.993 --> 20:58.344
I know he's not the child
that we envisioned,

20:58.474 --> 21:00.563
but he's ours.

21:04.698 --> 21:07.570
It's God's will
that we be strong.

21:09.572 --> 21:11.748
We have to be.

21:11.879 --> 21:13.359
For him.

21:18.886 --> 21:22.542
We have enough love between us
for this child, don't we?

21:28.896 --> 21:30.463
I do.

21:30.593 --> 21:32.639
So do I.

21:32.769 --> 21:35.555
Then let's leave this place.

21:35.685 --> 21:37.731
I've given birth,
we can go now,

21:37.861 --> 21:40.603
far away
where they won't find me.

21:40.734 --> 21:42.649
You're safe here.

21:42.779 --> 21:44.781
You're wrong, Martin.

21:44.912 --> 21:46.696
You don't know
what they're capable of.

21:51.788 --> 21:54.443
Nothing good will come from
staying in Preacher's Corners.

21:58.578 --> 22:00.449
We'll leave.

22:04.018 --> 22:07.413
I'll take you and our child;
we'll go to California.

22:09.589 --> 22:11.939
Now,

22:12.069 --> 22:14.463
what shall we name him?
[chuckles]

22:31.088 --> 22:39.923
♪♪♪

23:09.605 --> 23:18.484
♪♪♪

23:18.614 --> 23:27.014
♪♪♪

23:41.028 --> 23:41.855
[whispers]
Mr. Boone.

23:43.117 --> 23:44.640
Did everything go well?

23:44.771 --> 23:46.816
Yes.

23:46.947 --> 23:50.603
I mean, uh, I made my case.

23:50.733 --> 23:51.908
I feel hopeful.

23:52.039 --> 23:53.562
Oh, that's good.

23:56.347 --> 23:59.568
I was just going
to pour myself a drink.

23:59.699 --> 24:02.745
[fire crackling]

24:02.876 --> 24:04.007
Thank you.

24:06.619 --> 24:10.013
Much of my life I spent
building fortunes for others.

24:12.973 --> 24:15.976
Whaling is lucrative
for those on top;

24:16.106 --> 24:17.978
it exploits those below.

24:18.108 --> 24:19.675
Especially the whale.

24:19.806 --> 24:21.938
Mm.

24:22.069 --> 24:23.810
Him most of all.

24:26.290 --> 24:30.251
Yes. Well, hopefully
with this new venture,

24:30.381 --> 24:32.906
there's enough profit
for everyone.

24:33.036 --> 24:34.908
I admire your ideals,
Mr. Boone.

24:35.038 --> 24:37.606
Charles. Please.

24:39.869 --> 24:42.698
It takes purpose
to break the paradigms

24:42.829 --> 24:44.744
that others set for us.

24:44.874 --> 24:46.702
As a woman, I know this well.

24:49.400 --> 24:50.619
Purpose.

24:54.884 --> 24:57.147
And what is yours, Miss Morgan?

24:57.278 --> 24:59.759
I hope to support myself
through writing.

24:59.889 --> 25:00.890
Fiction.

25:01.021 --> 25:04.024
I find power and freedom
in words

25:04.154 --> 25:06.113
that I don't always find
in life.

25:07.157 --> 25:10.291
I haven't traveled the way
you and your children have,

25:10.421 --> 25:14.469
but in my mind,
through invention, I do travel.

25:14.600 --> 25:17.907
I suspected a scribe
in our midst.

25:18.038 --> 25:19.996
- Inky hand.
- [chuckles]

25:21.868 --> 25:23.086
And a taste for whiskey.

25:28.135 --> 25:30.877
We're fortunate to have you,
Miss Morgan.

25:31.007 --> 25:32.879
Rebecca.

25:36.926 --> 25:39.146
To purpose.

25:39.276 --> 25:40.539
Purpose.

25:49.025 --> 25:52.115
[rattling, scurrying]

25:55.902 --> 25:57.860
[rattling, scurrying]

26:01.298 --> 26:03.736
[rattling, creaking]

26:03.866 --> 26:05.085
Blood calls...blood calls...

26:05.215 --> 26:06.782
Blood calls blood.

26:06.913 --> 26:07.696
[roars]

26:09.002 --> 26:09.959
It's coming.

26:10.090 --> 26:10.873
[roars]

26:11.004 --> 26:12.222
♪♪♪

26:12.353 --> 26:13.746
The worm is calling.

26:18.185 --> 26:19.578
[pounds loudly]

26:27.847 --> 26:28.935
[sighs]

26:29.065 --> 26:36.725
[whip poor wills chant]

26:38.205 --> 26:42.731
[labored breathing]

26:42.862 --> 26:44.994
[knocking]

26:47.214 --> 26:51.131
[distant knocking]

26:51.261 --> 26:54.221
[knocking repeats]

27:03.273 --> 27:04.231
- Father!
- Shh!

27:04.361 --> 27:05.754
Stay back.

27:08.235 --> 27:10.237
[doorknob rattling]

27:10.367 --> 27:11.760
- Who's there?
- [cocks gun]

27:13.370 --> 27:18.767
[rattling, pounding]

27:20.116 --> 27:21.944
It's a child.

27:27.036 --> 27:28.037
Hello?

27:40.136 --> 27:42.095
Is my papa here?

27:42.225 --> 27:43.792
Is that the girl from town?

27:43.923 --> 27:45.794
It's Susan Mallory.

27:45.925 --> 27:47.274
She must be freezing.

27:47.404 --> 27:49.842
Children, back away!
Back away!

27:49.972 --> 27:51.495
Tane, get a blanket.

27:51.626 --> 27:53.019
Where did she come from?

27:53.149 --> 27:55.282
She must've walked from town.

27:55.412 --> 27:57.153
Susan.

27:57.284 --> 27:59.025
Susan, wake up.

27:59.155 --> 28:01.070
Can you help me find Papa?

28:04.421 --> 28:05.727
Susan!

28:09.165 --> 28:13.169
[breathing rapidly]

28:13.300 --> 28:15.215
Where am I?

28:15.345 --> 28:17.173
- Where's Mother?
- You're okay.

28:17.304 --> 28:19.001
I'll take her home.
I know where she lives.

28:19.132 --> 28:21.221
- I'll go.
- It's best if I go alone.

28:21.351 --> 28:24.093
Rebecca, she has the illness.

28:24.224 --> 28:26.095
I know.
I have to get the girl home.

28:26.226 --> 28:28.794
I'll be careful.
Okay.

28:28.924 --> 28:29.838
It's okay.

28:34.974 --> 28:36.366
You are no better than them!

28:36.497 --> 28:38.194
Stay away from my family!

28:38.325 --> 28:40.283
I'm sorry.
I hope Susan feels better.

28:40.414 --> 28:42.111
What have they done
with my husband?!

28:54.950 --> 29:03.524
♪♪♪

29:03.654 --> 29:07.136
[clanging]

29:25.372 --> 29:27.026
[Honor] What happens
to people with the illness?

29:29.637 --> 29:34.207
They typically grow confused,
like the girl last night.

29:34.337 --> 29:39.255
And then they tire,
and become bedridden.

29:39.386 --> 29:40.953
And in some cases...

29:41.083 --> 29:42.084
They die?

29:44.130 --> 29:45.218
Yes.

29:47.176 --> 29:48.961
[Honor]
It sounds like consumption.

29:49.091 --> 29:51.093
That's how our mother died.

30:01.321 --> 30:06.935
♪♪♪

30:07.066 --> 30:08.197
[snorts]

30:08.328 --> 30:14.116
♪♪♪

30:14.247 --> 30:19.426
♪♪♪

30:27.216 --> 30:28.827
[groans]

30:30.480 --> 30:31.960
[grunts]

30:35.181 --> 30:37.923
[breathing heavily]

30:39.228 --> 30:40.969
[groans]

30:43.145 --> 30:44.233
[groans]

30:46.496 --> 30:47.933
[moans]

30:49.412 --> 30:51.980
[moans in pain]

31:08.170 --> 31:11.347
[breathing heavily]

31:16.396 --> 31:18.964
Where, w-where are my shells?

31:19.094 --> 31:20.313
I don't know.

31:20.443 --> 31:22.706
- Where did you hide them?
- I didn't.

31:22.837 --> 31:24.404
- I don't have 'em.
- I don't believe you.

31:24.534 --> 31:25.709
Tane, those were Mom's shells.

31:25.840 --> 31:27.233
If you're playing a game
on Loa, it's not--

31:27.363 --> 31:28.234
I didn't take 'em!

31:33.239 --> 31:34.544
He doesn't have them, Loa.

31:34.675 --> 31:36.155
Sit down and eat.

31:40.376 --> 31:41.464
I can help you look
for them after school.

31:41.595 --> 31:43.162
I'm sure they're around.

31:49.429 --> 31:58.525
♪♪♪

31:58.655 --> 32:01.267
[knocking on door]

32:01.397 --> 32:04.052
Faith, it's Alice Burroughs.

32:11.494 --> 32:13.192
- Mrs. Burroughs.
- Good afternoon, Faith.

32:13.322 --> 32:15.237
May I come in?

32:15.368 --> 32:17.196
Oh, this poor thing.

32:17.326 --> 32:18.675
What kind of a man
abandons a woman

32:18.806 --> 32:20.416
and leaves her
with such a burden?

32:20.547 --> 32:22.679
He's not a burden.

32:22.810 --> 32:26.335
I'm... I'm not here
to judge you, Faith.

32:26.466 --> 32:27.771
I want to help.

32:27.902 --> 32:29.338
I appreciate that.

32:29.469 --> 32:31.079
I'm doing fine.

32:32.907 --> 32:35.518
My husband has taken
an interest in your plight.

32:37.433 --> 32:39.479
He's been kind.

32:39.609 --> 32:41.655
As have others.

32:41.785 --> 32:44.136
You shouldn't have
to raise your child alone.

32:44.266 --> 32:45.964
Whoever the father is

32:46.094 --> 32:49.271
must be held responsible
for his part in this.

32:49.402 --> 32:52.274
Women in town talk.

32:52.405 --> 32:54.015
Many are concerned
that it might have been

32:54.146 --> 32:58.672
one of their husbands
who was tempted by your youth.

32:58.802 --> 33:01.153
- It wasn't.
- But it was someone.

33:01.283 --> 33:02.850
I can approach him for you.

33:02.981 --> 33:05.374
Why would you protect
someone who's done this to you?

33:05.505 --> 33:07.420
He doesn't love you, Faith.

33:11.467 --> 33:14.340
[baby's raspy breathing]

33:16.472 --> 33:19.519
My son needs only me.

33:19.649 --> 33:21.390
But thank you for stopping by.

33:23.566 --> 33:27.657
"Whoever conceals their sins
does not prosper,

33:27.788 --> 33:31.661
"but the one who confesses
and renounces them...

33:31.792 --> 33:33.315
finds mercy."

33:53.509 --> 33:54.554
What is this?

33:54.684 --> 33:56.382
It's a project
of my own design.

33:56.512 --> 33:58.601
You have leather and steel.

33:58.732 --> 34:00.038
Can you make it?

34:01.952 --> 34:03.476
I'll pay double to have it
done

34:03.606 --> 34:05.217
by day's end, Mister, uh...

34:05.347 --> 34:07.088
Joseph. Palmer.

34:12.311 --> 34:14.226
Thank you.

34:14.356 --> 34:15.749
Captain Boone,

34:15.879 --> 34:18.317
that pitch of yours
yesterday at the meeting?

34:18.447 --> 34:19.883
It's what the town needs.
We all know it,

34:20.014 --> 34:22.408
but we lived with Phillip
and Stephen Boone

34:22.538 --> 34:24.627
and we lived with
your grandmother's silence.

34:24.758 --> 34:27.108
You'll find it difficult
to change most minds.

34:28.501 --> 34:29.545
Well...

34:31.721 --> 34:34.202
I hope you're wrong,
Mr. Palmer.

34:46.562 --> 34:48.608
How much for the whale iron?

34:51.524 --> 34:58.618
♪♪♪

35:03.492 --> 35:04.754
How dare you show your face
in this town!

35:04.885 --> 35:06.495
My daughter is sick
with your illness!

35:06.626 --> 35:08.454
My husband is missing!

35:08.584 --> 35:09.890
- What have you done with him?
- I assure you, ma'am,

35:10.020 --> 35:12.414
I don't know who
or where your husband is.

35:12.545 --> 35:13.807
He lured my Susan
to Chapelwaite!

35:13.937 --> 35:15.635
- She's under his spell!
- I did no such thing.

35:15.765 --> 35:18.551
This!
This is the devil's book!

35:18.681 --> 35:20.727
Don't put your names in it!
[gasps]

35:20.857 --> 35:22.468
I am sorry for your troubles,

35:22.598 --> 35:23.686
but I'm conducting
business here.

35:23.817 --> 35:26.602
Don't touch me!
Leave us alone!

35:26.733 --> 35:28.213
Leave us all alone!

35:32.739 --> 35:34.654
Give up, Boone.

35:34.784 --> 35:36.917
- You'll get no men from here.
- No thanks to you.

35:37.047 --> 35:38.223
We don't want
your blood money.

35:39.746 --> 35:41.487
The future of this town--

35:41.617 --> 35:45.447
The future of this town
has nothing to do with you.

35:50.452 --> 35:51.497
You're a fool!

35:51.627 --> 35:52.715
The only harm you'll do

35:52.846 --> 35:54.674
is to the people
of Preacher's Corners!

36:01.768 --> 36:09.645
♪♪♪

36:24.486 --> 36:25.661
[liquid pouring]

36:25.792 --> 36:27.489
[children giggling]

36:28.795 --> 36:29.709
- [sighs]
- [child laughs]

36:29.839 --> 36:31.363
Come on, come on!

36:32.538 --> 36:34.714
Oh.

36:34.844 --> 36:36.585
- What's this?
- A costume.

36:36.716 --> 36:38.761
For All Hallows' Eve.
I have one also.

36:38.892 --> 36:41.808
We made them with Rebecca.

36:41.938 --> 36:43.766
We're sorry
you had a tough day.

36:43.897 --> 36:46.682
We know you probably don't want
to go back to town tonight,

36:46.813 --> 36:48.902
but maybe we can have
our own celebration here?

36:49.032 --> 36:51.252
We could stage a play.
I'll write a script.

36:55.082 --> 36:57.432
Mm. What do you want to do?

36:57.563 --> 36:59.347
You want to go to town?

37:02.872 --> 37:04.526
Honor, go put your costume on.

37:04.657 --> 37:06.833
[ giggles] Come on.

37:06.963 --> 37:08.487
Hope we get lots of treats!

37:10.967 --> 37:12.447
[knocking]

37:15.624 --> 37:16.712
Loa.

37:18.758 --> 37:20.760
The others are dressing
for Hallow's Eve.

37:33.947 --> 37:35.905
I was thinking of you today.

37:36.036 --> 37:38.517
I have something here

37:38.647 --> 37:40.562
that I hope will
brighten your spirits.

37:45.001 --> 37:45.741
Hm?

37:49.571 --> 37:50.659
I designed this for you.

37:53.009 --> 37:54.402
May I?

38:07.067 --> 38:09.374
It's lighter
with leather at the knee.

38:12.115 --> 38:14.466
I think you'll find it
easier to maneuver.

38:21.777 --> 38:24.476
Well, what do you think?

38:26.434 --> 38:28.610
I hear there's a bit
of walking involved tonight.

38:30.090 --> 38:32.310
It would be a fine chance
to try it.

38:46.062 --> 38:47.803
Good...

38:47.934 --> 38:51.677
[indistinct chatter]

38:51.807 --> 38:54.157
They're crawling out
of the woodwork, Mary.

38:54.288 --> 38:56.725
Streets are filled
with all kinds of monsters.

38:56.856 --> 38:58.640
You ready?

38:58.771 --> 38:59.728
I'm a little tired.

38:59.859 --> 39:01.730
I think I'll stay home.

39:01.861 --> 39:03.776
Mm, why are you tired?

39:03.906 --> 39:06.082
[laughs]
I've been working all day.

39:06.213 --> 39:07.867
Hmm.
Are you running a fever?

39:09.129 --> 39:11.044
It's not the illness.

39:11.174 --> 39:12.698
- Mary...
- I'm fine.

39:15.004 --> 39:18.617
Now go protect the town from
all those ghosts and goblins.

39:18.747 --> 39:20.358
[chuckles]

39:25.928 --> 39:28.975
[children laughing,
chattering]

39:29.105 --> 39:39.768
♪♪♪

39:39.899 --> 39:41.988
[Honor] Why do they give out
treats and money?

39:42.118 --> 39:43.990
[Rebecca] It's payment.
We're supposed to pray

39:44.120 --> 39:47.341
for their departed loved ones
in exchange.

39:47.472 --> 39:48.951
No one does.
It's all about the treats.

39:49.082 --> 39:50.518
Can we try?

39:52.781 --> 39:55.610
Yeah. Well, Honor, take
your sister and brother.

39:56.568 --> 39:58.047
Don't forget my mother's
boarding house.

39:58.178 --> 39:59.788
She gives out chocolates.

39:59.919 --> 40:01.399
Watch them!

40:05.707 --> 40:08.580
[children chattering]

40:14.194 --> 40:16.631
She's moving much better.

40:16.762 --> 40:18.720
I wish I was able
to mend her feelings

40:18.851 --> 40:20.940
as well as her leg.

40:21.070 --> 40:23.116
Her heart is broken.

40:24.030 --> 40:26.859
I was about her age
when my father left us.

40:26.989 --> 40:30.079
Loa just needs to know
that her feelings are normal,

40:30.210 --> 40:31.907
and that you love her,

40:32.038 --> 40:33.953
and that she's safe.

40:42.091 --> 40:43.832
May we have a treat?

40:43.963 --> 40:45.660
I'm sorry.
You'll have to move along.

40:47.749 --> 40:49.055
Go on now.

40:51.753 --> 40:53.712
We'll try next door.

40:53.842 --> 40:55.453
[Tane]
Did we do something wrong?

40:58.107 --> 41:00.762
[Charles exhales]

41:00.893 --> 41:04.200
I didn't know these people
were capable of fun.

41:04.331 --> 41:06.681
Well, don't let them beat you.

41:06.812 --> 41:08.944
You have good ideas
for this town,

41:09.075 --> 41:11.033
even if they think
you might be crazy.

41:16.735 --> 41:18.737
Why do they think that?

41:18.867 --> 41:21.348
Well, anyone who spends time
in Chapelwaite

41:21.479 --> 41:24.612
is either a lunatic or
runs the risk of becoming one.

41:29.878 --> 41:31.053
It's just a rumor,
Mr. Boone.

41:34.404 --> 41:36.145
I mean, isn't that
what ambitions are:

41:36.276 --> 41:38.757
a form of madness?

41:38.887 --> 41:41.063
Isn't a sliver of lunacy
what it takes

41:41.194 --> 41:43.631
to dream beyond
the realm of the ordinary?

41:45.851 --> 41:47.592
I suppose you're right.

41:50.812 --> 41:51.900
- Thank you.
- There you are.

41:52.031 --> 41:52.727
Thank you.

41:55.730 --> 41:56.644
[squeals]

41:56.775 --> 41:57.819
- Oh!
- [laughs]

41:57.950 --> 41:59.952
- Stop it!
- That'll lighten you up!

42:00.082 --> 42:01.649
Let go of me!

42:03.259 --> 42:04.957
You want to apologize
to these people?

42:05.087 --> 42:06.175
I ain't apologizin'
for shite, darkie.

42:06.306 --> 42:07.786
- My pa says--
- [slap]

42:12.312 --> 42:14.053
I'm gonna get my pa.

42:14.183 --> 42:15.794
He's gonna fix
you filthy Boones!

42:19.319 --> 42:20.973
Do all you sailors
punch that hard?

42:22.627 --> 42:24.585
Do all you farm boys
fall that easy?

42:26.282 --> 42:28.110
Able.

42:28.241 --> 42:29.938
I work for your father.

42:33.768 --> 42:38.904
♪♪♪

42:39.034 --> 42:41.689
[whispering prayers]

42:45.040 --> 42:46.564
Is Papa here?

42:49.044 --> 42:50.219
No, sweetheart.

42:50.350 --> 42:53.048
He'll be here soon.

42:53.179 --> 42:54.876
Stephen will bring him.

42:55.007 --> 42:57.096
I'm sure he will.

43:02.884 --> 43:03.885
Stephen?

43:05.887 --> 43:07.715
We have to wait.

43:07.846 --> 43:11.153
[strained breathing]

43:15.897 --> 43:17.769
Here they come.

43:17.899 --> 43:19.858
That's him at the window.

43:22.382 --> 43:24.732
Let him in, Mama.

43:28.214 --> 43:30.738
Papa's here
with my friend Stephen.

43:32.087 --> 43:33.828
[quiet wheeze]

43:47.015 --> 43:50.889
[sobs]

44:00.159 --> 44:01.203
She's dead!

44:01.334 --> 44:03.379
My girl is dead!

44:03.510 --> 44:05.164
My baby is gone!
God have mercy.

44:06.382 --> 44:08.123
Where's my husband?

44:08.254 --> 44:10.299
Edward!
Edward!

44:10.430 --> 44:12.214
Find the children.
Get them somewhere safe.

44:12.345 --> 44:13.302
- What happened here?
- Edward!

44:13.433 --> 44:15.957
Susan Mallory passed.

44:16.088 --> 44:18.177
It was a Boone!
Stephen Boone killed my baby!

44:18.307 --> 44:20.570
Rose, please. Stephen Boone's
been dead over a year.

44:20.701 --> 44:22.268
He's back!
It was Stephen Boone!

44:22.398 --> 44:23.835
- She said so herself.
- She never said that.

44:23.965 --> 44:25.358
The child was delirious.

44:25.488 --> 44:28.491
She saw him!
Stephen Boone!

44:28.622 --> 44:30.058
- Clearly this woman needs help.
- Dig him up!

44:30.189 --> 44:32.278
Enough now!
This is insanity.

44:32.408 --> 44:34.106
- Prove it.
- I see you, sir.

44:34.236 --> 44:36.282
I see what you're doing here.

44:36.412 --> 44:38.153
Stephen Boone lives!

44:38.284 --> 44:39.981
We all know what they did!

44:40.112 --> 44:42.288
The Boones made an unholy pact
for that house and land.

44:42.418 --> 44:44.333
They're all cursed!
And we are too!

44:44.464 --> 44:46.118
If you all believe
this is true,

44:46.248 --> 44:47.946
then there really is
no hope for this town.

44:48.076 --> 44:50.165
On my life,
you will never know peace!

44:50.296 --> 44:51.253
- On--
- [gunshot]

44:52.994 --> 44:54.692
Go home.

44:56.476 --> 44:58.304
Hallows' Eve is over.

45:00.654 --> 45:03.091
[Rose sobbing]

45:14.450 --> 45:16.061
- [tapping, clicking]
- [gasps]

45:24.156 --> 45:25.853
George?

45:34.470 --> 45:35.994
George?

45:54.142 --> 46:00.279
♪♪♪

46:00.409 --> 46:02.368
- [whip-poor-wills chirp]
- Whoa.

46:02.498 --> 46:04.587
[chirping continues]

46:04.718 --> 46:05.980
Everyone in the house.

46:06.111 --> 46:07.286
Are you all right,
Mr. Boone?

46:07.416 --> 46:09.331
Rebecca, put the children
to bed straight away.

46:09.462 --> 46:10.942
- Father!
- Do as you're told.

46:11.072 --> 46:12.204
[Rebecca] Come on.

46:17.644 --> 46:19.907
Everyone to their rooms.
You heard your father.

46:30.091 --> 46:32.050
[breathing heavily]

46:41.494 --> 46:43.452
You want peace?

46:43.583 --> 46:45.803
You want to see if he lies
where he should?

46:49.371 --> 46:51.112
My God.

46:51.243 --> 47:00.165
♪♪♪

47:00.295 --> 47:05.823
[otherworldly hissing]

47:07.128 --> 47:08.347
On your life,

47:08.477 --> 47:10.349
I swear I'll drag
the son of a bitch

47:10.479 --> 47:12.133
down Main Street and plant him
on the church steps.

47:12.264 --> 47:13.134
[thud]

47:22.274 --> 47:29.847
♪♪♪

47:36.114 --> 47:45.340
♪♪♪
